In most hands  the glucose oxidase strip method is accurate and reliable 
Since whole blood is used  the results tend to be slightly lower than simultaneous venous samples  but this is balanced by the fact that capillary blood has a higher glucose concentration than venous blood 
Most patients can visually estimate the correct value  but a few patients consistently misread the visual charts and must use a reflectance meter 
This may be due to an unexpectedly high prevalence of disturbances of color perception in diabetics 
Most patients feel more comfortable with the digital readout of the reflectance meter  although it is not necessarily more accurate 
The major sources of error are in failing to put a large enough drop of blood on the strip and inaccurate timing 
For patients who use reflectance meters  another source of error is failure to keep the machine clean and calibrated 
Once the color is developed  it is relatively stable  so patients can be instructed to bring developed strips to the physician's office so that the accuracy can be checked 
