The oral glucose tolerance test is fraught with potential problems  and strict adherence to protocol must be followed to reach a valid conclusion 
Patients must not be experiencing acute medical or surgical stress 
They should be tested several months after recovery 
Patients who are chronically malnourished or who have been carbohydrate restricted will have exaggerated blood sugar responses 
In general  the patient should have at least a  g carbohydrate intake and normal physical activity for  days preceding the test 
Patients who have been confined to bed for  or more days should also have the test delayed until after recovery 
If possible  patients should discontinue all medications for  days prior to testing 
Patients who have undergone a recent gastrectomy should be watched carefully for alimentary hypoglycemia 
